6. What Happens Internally
When you run:
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml
Kubernetes performs:
Step 1:Deployment createdStep 
Step 2:Deployment creates ReplicaSet
Step 3:ReplicaSet creates 3 Pods
Step 4:Pods run containers

Architecture:
Deployment    
↓
ReplicaSet 3

↓ Pods

7. ReplicaSet Role

ReplicaSet continuously checks:
Desired Pods = 3Current Pods = ?

Pod Failure Example

Suppose one Pod crashes.
Current state:
Current Pods = 2 Desired Pods = 3

ReplicaSet automatically creates new Pod.
Self-healing achieved.

8. Scaling

Increase replicas:
kubectl scale deployment ecommerce-app --replicas=5
Now Kubernetes creates:
5 Pods

Architecture:
Deployment    
↓
ReplicaSet    
↓
5 Pods

9. Rolling Update

Suppose developers release:
ecommerce-app:v2

Update YAML:
image: ecommerce-app:v2

Apply update:
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

10. Rolling Update Process

Kubernetes does NOT stop all Pods immediately.

Instead:
Old Pods replaced gradually

Initial State
Pod-1 v1
Pod-2 v1
Pod-3 v1

Update Starts
Kubernetes creates new Pod:

Pod-1 v1
Pod-2 v1
Pod-3 v1
Pod-4 v2

After new Pod becomes healthy:

Pod-1 v1 removed
Process continues gradually.

Final state:
Pod-A v2
Pod-B v2
Pod-C v2

11. Internal ReplicaSets During Update

Before update:
ReplicaSet-v1 active

After update:
ReplicaSet-v2 created

Architecture:
Deployment    
↓
ReplicaSet-v2    
↓
Pods running v2

ReplicaSet-v1 still stored

12. Production Failure Example

Suppose v2 contains payment bug.
Users report:
Payments failing
Production issue occurs.

13. Rollback
Rollback command:
kubectl rollout undo deployment/ecommerce-app

14. What Rollback Does

Kubernetes performs:
Scale down ReplicaSet-v2 Scale up ReplicaSet-v1

Architecture changes back:
Deployment    
↓
ReplicaSet-v1    
↓
Pods running v1

Application restored.

15. Rollback to Specific Revision
Check history:
kubectl rollout history deployment/ecommerce-app

Example:
REVISION    IMAGE1           v12           v2

Rollback to revision 1:
kubectl rollout undo deployment/ecommerce-app --to-revision=1

16. Why Deployment is Powerful
Deployment provides:
scaling
self-healing
rolling updates
rollback
version history

17. Important Commands

Apply Deployment
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml

View Deployments
kubectl get deployments

View ReplicaSets
kubectl get rs

View Pods
kubectl get pods

Scale Application
kubectl scale deployment ecommerce-app --replicas=5

Check Rollout Status
kubectl rollout status deployment/ecommerce-app

Rollout History
kubectl rollout history deployment/ecommerce-app

Rollback pervious Version
kubectl rollout undo deployment/ecommerce-app

Rollback Specific Revision
kubectl rollout undo deployment/ecommerce-app --to-revision=1

18. Complete Lifecycle
Developer writes Deployment YAML            ↓kubectl apply            ↓Deployment created            ↓Deployment creates ReplicaSet            ↓ReplicaSet creates Pods            ↓Pods run containers            ↓Users access application            ↓Scaling possible            ↓Updates possible            ↓Rollback possible

19. Final Understanding
Think of Kubernetes like this:
Deployment = Project ManagerReplicaSet = SupervisorPods = WorkersContainers = Actual Applications

Deployment decides desired state

ReplicaSet maintains Pod count

Pods host containers

Containers run applications

Rollback works because:

old ReplicaSets are preserved

Deployment can switch back anytime


This provides:
high availability
zero/minimal downtime
safe production deployments
